reviews.text:
"Mine's bigger."  

This phrase sums up my childhood memories of Graeter's. (Yes, it's also a line from National Lampoon's Animal House.). Who was patient enough to excavate--by spoon, tongue, or fingers (whatevs...we were kids)--the BOULDERS of chocolate that were encased in ice cream? We dug, we compared, we gloated. MINE IS BIGGER.  Then we ate those enormous slabs of chocolate like the greedy, ungrateful children that we were. 

I'm an adult now, and while I can still eat Graeter's ice cream like Jim Belishi in line at the cafeteria, I've picked up a few nuggets  of experience and knowledge about lots of things, including the following about Graeter's;

1. Those BOULDERS are quality, dark chocolate, a girl's best friend;
2. When you carry a dozen cherry cheese crowns onto an airplane as a gift to your Florida aunt, other passengers will offer to buy them from you;
3. Graeter's ice cream is made by a French process that roughy translates into English as, "cold bliss mouth";
4. If you send only one box of Opera Cremes as a gift, your aunt may hide them from your uncle, thereby causing marital strife (send TWO boxes, clearly marked for each recipient);
5. Glazed Happiness [doughnuts] are not false advertising;
6. Arrive early (before 9 a.m.) if you would like Glazed Happiness on Fridays;
7. Seasonal flavors, e.g., Strawberry Chip and Watermelon Sorbet, will possibly send you into the stratosphere (Moral: Keep an open mind!).

I write now because the Graeter's store nearest to my workplace is being renovated--a veritable first-world, dearth of happiness! This absence, unlike others that have inspired exploration of other possibilities, has def made my heart grow fonder.
